idian\n\n2024-04-12 07:49:46\n\n45| 13  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nNo teacher's union that I'm familiar with has any problem with the idea that\nmath teachers should make more than PE teachers. They just notice that in the\nstates where they can't collectively bargain, everyone makes less, even the\nmath teacher. You're measuring a second-order effect which we all know is\nthere (pay for performance) while ignoring the primary driver of the wages of\nteachers, which is the monopsony power of the state.\n\nRespond\n\n### Etalon d'Silomar\n\n2024-04-12 09:09:46\n\n61| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nHow are math teachers paid by charter schools, relative to math teachers in\nunionized public schools in the same town? But this is another meaningless\ncomparison because it's not the same job, because charters get to select\nstudents in a way that publics do not.\n\nRespond\n\n### (Not That) Bill O'Reilly\n\n2024-04-12 09:40:42\n\n85| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nCharters also don't have to limit their hiring pool to over-credentialed\nEducation/Math double-majors with an advanced degree.\n\nRespond\n\n### steve\n\n2024-04-12 11:54:30\n\n20| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nYet it seems like the principle should still apply ie if you pay more you get\nbetter teachers. Yet in private schools where presumably the market is\nfunctioning they generally pay less than public schools. They dont generally\nselectively pay teachers a lot differently. I totally get that in the current\nexample Alex provides that if a school pays a lot more than a neighboring\nschool they can hire away teachers from the lower paying school that they\nperceive as being superior, mostly based upon experience, but how will it work\non a larger scale?\n\nSteve\n\nRespond\n\n### Roger Sweeny\n\n2024-04-12 10:34:27\n\n44| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAll the teachers unions around here do have a \"problem with the idea that math\nteachers should make more than PE teachers\", here bein