ECD argued that teachers in the US\ntend to get a relatively large anti-premium matched against other college\ngraduates (about 65% of the average college graduate).\n\nPartly, this seems maybe linked to the fact that the post tax graduate\nearnings premium (again per OECD) in the US seems relatively high (about 40%\nvs OECD average about 20%). (Some folks disputed that this was actually such a\nbad deal, citing limited US mandatory holiday/vacation vs generous teacher\nsummer holidays, compared to Europe with more statutory holiday).\n\nOECD also found that, comparing systems, \"no relationship between average\nstudent performance in a country and the use of performance-based pay schemes\"\nbut with the caveat that \"in countries with comparatively low teachers\u2019\nsalaries (less than 15% above GDP per capita), student performance tends to be\nbetter when performance-based pay systems are in place, while in countries\nwhere teachers are relatively well-paid (more than 15% above GDP per capita),\nthe opposite is true\".\n\nSo is performance related pay, as a unique incentive itself operating much\nhere, or is it just primarily acting as a correction for relatively low\nteacher pay, and that perhaps the price of primary and secondary education\n(wages) needs to go up?\n\nRespond\n\n### that makes a lot of sense\n\n2024-04-12 08:58:54\n\n80| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n> So is performance related pay, as a unique incentive itself operating much\n> here, or is it just primarily acting as a correction for relatively low\n> teacher pay\n\nIt gets fiendishly hard to sort teacher quality separate from student quality.\nWe used to joke about whose turn it was to be the best teacher in the school,\nbased on class draws.\n\nI can see where in grossly underfunded areas, incentive pay might help the\ncream rise from the curds. \"Underpay young people and allow them to make more\nfrom doing extra\" is also the formula that gets you coaches and after school\nprograms.\n\nI can't think of an admin that WOULDN'T want to pay for performance, but\nthere's are reasons that this old chestnut lays around untouched for the most\npart, and the teacher unions were the sole roadblock, then the right-to-work\nstates would be rolling in the dividends of merit pay, and that hasn't\nhappened.\n\nRespond\n\n### another consideration\n\n2024-04-12 09:12:47\n\n80| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"Teaching effectiveness\" isn't just the domain of K-12.\n\nGiven the costs of higher ed and the importance of non-academic training, some\nmetrics and rewards in these fields based on student outcomes, not fuzzy\nfeelings and bullet-riddled CVs, seem in order. Maybe I've missed the interest\nthere.\n\nRespond\n\n### Roger Sweeny\n\n2024-04-12 10:45:01\n\n44| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"We used to joke about whose turn it was to be the best teacher in the school,\nbased on class draws.\"\n\nYes! Yes! Yes! Back when I taught four honors physics classes, the average\nmarks (and the marks on the mid-term and final) were different in each of the\nfour classes, with one class usually the obvious worst. Yet I was the same\nteacher in each. I did not magically become a good teacher in one and a bad\nteacher in another.\n\nRespond\n\n### blue jay\n\n2024-04-12 08:41:42\n\n28| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nDoes one's answer to that depends on whether your a good math teacher or a\nshitty social studies teacher?\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 08:56:29\n\n4| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nWhat do you mean by that?\n\nRespond\n\n### blue jay\n\n2024-04-12 12:01:44\n\n13| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n?? I'm not sure it's mysterious. If you're a good teacher with credentials\nthat demand higher pay, you're likely to view performance pay as an important\nincentive. If you're not a good teacher and/or have a specialty that has\nlittle independent value, you're sure to claim that general higher pay is the\nreal factor - and thereby advocate for generally 