nformation.\n\n\\--Is the test properly utilized? In other words: What, fundamentally, is the\npoint of testing? Ideally we'd use testing to identify areas of weakness in\nthe student body's understanding of a topic, and focus teaching efforts on\nthose areas of weakness. Realistically, few teachers do that and I don't know\nof any administration that does. They use the test scores as performance\nmetrics for the class and the teacher.\n\n\\--How much time is spent on test-taking techniques? Classes like ACT prep\nclasses and the like basically teach students how to game the system. Not how\nto cheat, but rather how to take tests more effectively regardless of content.\nThere's not no value in this, but the majority of the value is going to be to\na handful of students (those with learning disabilities and severe test\nanxiety, for example), most of whom aren't the type to take these sorts of\nclasses (or at least to take them seriously).\n\n\\--How does one distinguish between student contribution and teacher\ncontribution to test scores? This entire discussion is focused on teachers,\nbut education, fundamentally, is what the student does. The teacher can\nfacilitate, but it's up to the students do decide whether they're going to\nlearn or not. This is part of what I mentioned elsewhere about administrations\nand parents not supporting the teachers--if we view the test results as only\nthe teachers' responsibility, we give students a free pass to screw around.\nEducation becomes something that happens to students, not something students\nare actively participating in.\n\nRespond\n\n### TMC\n\n2024-04-12 10:40:05\n\n13| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nExactly. \"Teaching to the test\", AKA learning math, tends to produce kids who\nknow math.\n\nRespond\n\n### PHinton\n\n2024-04-12 09:55:50\n\n30| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nAhhh, yes. The claim that our teachers are teaching kids \"how to think\" and\nnot just pass a test like an automaton.\n\nWe should be so lucky to have a classroom of kids that could ace math tests\nbut not know how, precisely, they managed.\n\nBecause what we have today are classrooms of kids that know nothing. A\nclassroom that has 5% math proficiency at grade level has failed. And it's the\nteacher and school that has failed. And all they can muster is \"we need more\nmoney.\"\n\nRespond\n\n### Etalon d'Silomar\n\n2024-04-12 10:03:35\n\n60| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nNo, the vast majority of what influences student performance happens outside\nthe school. Much of it happens before the student is even born.\n\nRespond\n\n### PHinton\n\n2024-04-12 10:47:54\n\n30| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nYes, of course. But that wasn't the point I was making.\n\nRespond\n\n### Sashoir\n\n2024-04-12 09:29:04\n\n28| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nI've not seen (I did have a casual look, a few years ago) any real evidence\nfor performance (however measured) gains from teacher-pupil matching. In my\nown experience (which is not meaningful evidence), some teachers were good for\nsome students, and not others, a very few teachers were good for all but the\nmost incorrigible, and some were rubbish for all pupils. I have seen evidence\nof the equivalent in the workplace context.\n\nI don't see much hope in public policy-driven improvements unless and until\nteachers, the academic education establishment, parents, and politicians put\naway their various axes: and everyone seems to enjoy grinding them far too\nmuch for that to happen.\n\nRespond\n\n### Mike in Va\n\n2024-04-12 10:36:21\n\n32| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAt least in observing my daughters' performance of various teachers, the\nsingle biggest factor is how many misbehaving students were placed in a given\nclass.\n\nThe best teachers for my daughters are the ones who are best able to handle\nthe misbehaving students or are lucky enough to not be assigned many\nmisbehaving students.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 09:47:07\n\n27| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nThis evaluation avoids the most important question: What constitutes a high-\nquality teacher? The fundamental problem facing the education industry right\nnow is that the needs of the population are shifting, and the criteria for\nmeasuring success are no longer valid. Until we get that straightened out, any\nassessment on how to improve quality is premature.\n\nTake gym teachers. Most of the ones I've known were merely coaches who were\nhanded a \"class\" that didn't really matter, so they couldn't screw it up.\nThere's logic to the idea that healthy bodies are necessary for healthy minds,\nbut the reality is that most gym classes don't do much for that, and any\nsociety that removes recess and other physical activities from children's\nlives doesn't really care about physical fitness anyway. Basically, as long as\nno one dies and the gym teacher meets the criteria necessary to coach whatever\nsport they coach, they've done their job.\n\nFor other teachers, the de facto criteria for quality are student test scores,\nhow many students are failing, and how many students enroll in college.\nFundamentally our schools are not educating students, they're training\nstudents on how to take tests. There's some logic to using test scores--if the\ntest measure stuff we think our citizen body should know, it makes sense to\nuse that as a framework (there are pedagogical theories on structuring classes\nthis way)--but, well, this is an economics blog. Any metric used to measure\nperformance thereby becomes a poor measure of performance. Student performance\nonly makes sense if you've never been a teacher and know nothing of population\nstatistics; there's a certain percent in any large body that is hopeless, and\nto blame teachers for student behavior is irrational. As for university\nattendance, this is perhaps the biggest con in our culture right now. The idea\nthat all students need a university education is false, pure and simple. If a\nkid learns what they need in high school to start working for their dad's HVAC\nbusiness, that should be counted as a win--he's a contributing member of\nsociety learning an increasingly valuable skillset--but currently it's counted\nas a failure on the school's part.\n\nRight now, if you want a job in corporate America, the most in-demand skills\nare interpersonal skills. Conflict management, team building, working with\npeople you don't like--these soft skills that used to be learned on the\nplayground and in the back yard. If you have descent time management and\norganizational skills, even better. This is only going to become more\nimportant as time goes on. And unfortunately the criteria we're evaluating\nteacher performance on are actively undermining attempts at teaching kids\nthese skills.\n\nRespond\n\n### OldCurmudgeon\n\n2024-04-12 11:22:39\n\n51| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n>This evaluation avoids the most important question: What constitutes a high-\nquality teacher?\n\nThe answer probably depends on each particular kid...which sorta implies\nthings that allow better matching (e.g., school choice, charter schools,\nspecial programs, etc.) may be more important than individual teacher metrics.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 11:39:17\n\n24| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThat still avoids the question of what the purpose of education is. Right now\nthe de facto answer is \"To get kids into college\", which merely kicks the can\ndown a very expensive road.\n\nThat aside, I'm not entirely unsympathetic to this view, but I think it can be\n(and usually is) taken too far. Again, it focuses on the teacher to the\nexclusion of the other components of a child's education. The child is the\nother major component to consider--and it's good for children to learn to work\nwith and for various types of people (of all the things you learn in school\nthis may be the most useful in the working world!). Further, parents and\nadministrations play a role here. A parent that works with the teacher, rather\nthan working against them, can result in a match that initially appears to be\npoor to really blossom. The thing is, parents have a better perspective than\nstudents on what constitutes a good fit--students are naturally going to want\neasy teachers, because that makes their life easier. A good parent wants\nharder teachers, because they push the student.\n\nAs for administrations, their role is to provide good systems and support for\nteachers and students (with the caveat that they're supposed to do what's best\nfor the students, NOT what the students and parents think is best). While\npolicies and procedures get a bad rap in our society, they really are\ncritical. Good policies and procedures establish systems that allow even\nlower-tier people in a role to do a reasonable job. They can sometimes\nconstrain top-tier people, but that's not always a bad thing (pedagogy is more\nheavily influenced by fads than I'd like; it's a young field, as these things\ngo).\n\nRespond\n\n### Mike in Va\n\n2024-04-12 11:07:04\n\n32| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"\"The idea that all students need a university education is false, pure and\nsimple. If a kid learns what they need in high school to start working for\ntheir dad's HVAC business, that should be counted as a win--he's a\ncontributing member of society learning an increasingly valuable skillset--but\ncurrently it's counted as a failure on the school's part\"\"\n\nOne thing the public school system in my county gets right is that they\nevaluate the school system by how many of its graduating seniors have a job,\njoin the military or are attending college (2 or 4 year). The hardest classes\nto get into are the Vo-Tech classes (welding, culinary arts, hair styling,\ncarpentry and HVAC). This provides for a number of certifications that\nstudents can obtain before they graduate in order to get a good job out of\nhigh school.\n\nAt the same time they still offer accelerates academics for students who are\nacademically inclined. My eldest daughter is in the governor's school and a\nprogram that will allow her to take enough college courses that she will\ngraduate with an associate's degree before she graduates from high school.\n\nThe school does not have good SOL scores, so it is not a highly rated school.\nBut it does allow students who are not gifted towards academics to learn\nvaluable skills that will help them have successful lives.\n\nRespond\n\n### PHinton\n\n2024-04-12 10:21:49\n\n31| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n> What constitutes a high-quality teacher?\n\nThe difference between a good teacher and excellent teacher probably aren't\nthat much. An excellent teacher could take a great student under her wing and\nopen up an entire universe of learning, give direction on colleges, etc.\n\nThe problem we have right now isn't good/great. It's good versus bad.\n\nThe bad teachers lose control of a classroom and just starting counting the\ndays until summer break arrives. Kids on phone during class? No problem. Kids\nvaping during class? No problem. Kids running around? No problem.\n\nthose teachers allow the bad eggs to dominate the classroom, and screw up the\nlearning for the few that do want to learn.\n\nSo, don't focus on the good versus great. Focus on the lousy teachers that are\nso poor at their job they are hurting kids and not just failing to elevate\nthem.\n\nit is very sad that a single bad kid and a weak teacher (and administration)\ncan ruin learning for the 29 other kids. That is happening every single day.\nFocus on that first.\n\nRespond\n\n### Roger Sweeny\n\n2024-04-12 10:55:44\n\n44| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"Classroom management\", the modern term for \"maintaining order\" is partly a\nteacher thing but is even more an administration thing. The teacher is the\nfirst line, but when that fails, admin has to make a serious effort get and\nkeep disruptive students on a path that doesn't sacrifice the other students.\nIf the teacher thinks, \"I want to send X out of the class but he'll just be\nsent back\" that's when you get \"teachers lose control of a classroom\".\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 10:40:10\n\n26| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n\"The problem we have right now isn't good/great. It's good versus bad.\"\n\nI'm not asking where on the scale we're talking about. I'm asking what metric\nto use. Someone who's good at an irrelevant skillset isn't of much value in\nany job.\n\nAs for the rest, classroom discipline got far less to do with the teachers\nthan you believe. Teachers can only maintain classroom discipline as long as\nthe administration has their back, and most simply do not. Any time Junior\nfails an assignment the parents come in breathing fire at the teachers and the\nadministration will usually cave (at least in the school districts I've been\nin). Kids aren't stupid; once they see that the administration will punish the\nteachers for the students' misbehavior, the students will misbehave. And after\na teacher is punished a few times for enforcing school rules, they learn to\nkeep quiet and keep their heads down.\n\nIf you want to maintain classroom discipline the teachers are the LAST place\nto focus. You need parents willing to support the schools in punishing\nstudents that violate policies, and you need administrations that default to\nsupporting the teachers when they discipline the students. If you don't have\nthose, there's literally nothing teachers can do about classroom discipline.\n\nThis isn't unique to schools. This is a fairly common managerial problem, one\nwith fairly well-established fixes. But people tend to think that education is\nsomehow unique and thus normal managerial rules don't apply.\n\n(To be fair, we're talking about a minority of teachers here. And it's telling\nthat so many people on this blog base their entire understanding of the\neducation system on baseless stereotypes, outright lies, and minority cases.)\n\nRespond\n\n### PHinton\n\n2024-04-12 11:01:07\n\n28| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n> Teachers can only maintain classroom discipline as long as the\n> administration has their back\n\nBingo. Which is why I said \"a weak teacher (and administration) can ruin\nlearning for the 29 other kids\"\n\nAnd you note, this doesn't just apply to school, but work too. A bad engineer\non a product development team is a HUGE liability.\n\nBack to your point: The difference between good and great teachers is, at this\nstage of the game, irrelevant. We need the ability to get rid of bad teachers\nquickly, and clear out the performative troublemaking kids that are working to\nensure the entire class is centered on them.\n\nThat is step 1. And our school administrators have already said they aren't\nkeen to fix either. And so, the bad apples will continue ruining the learning\nof 29 others.\n\n> (To be fair, we're talking about a minority of teachers here.\n\nAre you sure? 20-25% of classes were ruined according to my kids. The school\nwas attended by lots of MSFT families. Whites were overrepresented (vs\nnational), Asian way overrepresented, and blacks way underrepresented. And it\nwas the more rural white kids that were turning the classroom into their own\npersonal stage.\n\nA K12 education for a family of two is a \"gift\" of $400K to a family. That we\ndon't protect the value of this gift is insane. But the mentality of school\nadministrators today is to not punish and let the $400K gift be driven towards\nzero.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 11:21:24\n\n24| 2  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n\"Which is why I said \"a weak teacher (and administration) can ruin learning\nfor the 29 other kids\" \"\n\nAnd I'm saying that you are wrong.\n\nYou are blaming teachers for systematic failures of the ADMINSTRATION. Your\n\"solution\" is to fire teachers for those failures of the administration--which\nmeans your \"solution\" has as much chance of fixing the issue as applying a new\ncoat of paint has for fixing a transmission problem on a car.\n\nI've seen a number of managers think like you--blame the first person they\nidentify as a problem, dig no further, and pretend they fixed the problem. In\nconstruction, this gets people killed. There's a reason we waste time and\nmoney doing Root Cause Analyses--because the \"obvious\" person at fault usually\nisn't the actual problem. To really fix problems requires a deeper\ninvestigation.\n\n\"20-25% of classes were ruined according to my kids.\"\n\nAnd we all know that self-reported situations by students is the height of\nrigor...And 20-25% is now not a minority.....The mind simply boggles.\n\nRespond\n\n### PHinton\n\n2024-04-12 12:47:09\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n> You are blaming teachers for systematic failures of the ADMINSTRATION. Your\n> \"solution\" is to fire teachers for those failures of the administration-\n\nOK, then let's fire the administrators and replace them with administrators\nthat will remove bad kids from the class rooms in short order. AND THEN fire\nthe teachers that allow a bad apple to ruin the $400K learning experience for\nthe others.\n\nOf course, you'd have a million reasons why firing administrators and\nreplacing them with hard-nosed folks that don't put up with BS won't work\neither, right?\n\n> And we all know that self-reported situations by students is the height of\n> rigor\n\nA relative comparison by ANYONE is valid. That is why consumers are asked all\nthis time \"is X better or worse than Y?\" You might not like that a kid reports\nthat 1/5 of their classes were ruined by a bad apple. But it is what it is.\nit's just as valid as YOU saying \"Administrators are WORSE than teachers.\" You\noffered an OPINION without a hint of irony. And then, when you hear of someone\nelse offering an opinion, just as you did, you fall back to a weak argument\nfrom authority that a child cannot tell if something is better or worse.\n\nSo, yes, let's pretend the entire system is working well. But, nobody believes\nit is. Not the kids. Not the teachers. Not the administrators, Not even the\nteachers unions.\n\nRespond\n\n### Manzoni\n\n2024-04-12 11:48:26\n\n25| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\u201cPaying the best teachers more is good for teachers and great for students who\nsee increases in achievement which pay off many years later in higher wages.\u201d\nDo higher wages necessarily follow? If everybody knows more and competition\nholds it\u2019s zero-sum.\n\nRespond\n\n### rayward\n\n2024-04-12 08:01:59\n\n30| 7  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nThere's a very good reason teachers' salaries are not individually negotiated:\n\"good\" teachers would only want to work in \"good\" schools with \"good\" students\nso they can negotiate \"good\" salaries. Under Tabarrok's view, it's would\n\"good\" if the \"good\" teachers work in the \"good\" schools with \"good\" students,\nrewarding the \"good\" students with \"good\" teachers. That's how America works:\nreward exceptionalism, not mediocrity. I get it: I attended segregated (all\nwhite) public schools, where I benefited from having \"good\" teachers and\n\"good\" students (classmates). Today's version of segregation is to put \"good\"\nteachers with \"good\" students in \"good\" schools, not according to race but\nexceptionalism. There are winners and there are losers in life's lottery.\nLet's reward the winners.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dino the Isaurian\n\n2024-04-12 09:11:39\n\n63| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nThe underlying reality is that individual teachers do not matter much within\nthe system and there is no good way to measure the performance of individual\nteachers.*\n\nCrappy teachers do matter in a negative way, and everyone with a school knows\nwho they are. But above a minimum threshold they are fungible. Teachers\nthemselves know this, even if they won admit it, which is why they oppose\nincentive driven pay schemes.\n\n*The most important aspects of education are the children themselves, Their genetic potential, family stability, cultural background. The next most important aspects are the management of the school itself - the level of discipline enforced, the curriculum, the maintenance of the physical plant. The individual variance of the instructor is very far behind the other factors. And impossible to tease out and rank in any impartial way.\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 09:39:36\n\n41| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nIMO, individual teachers COULD make a difference, if they were working in\norganizations that allowed the better teachers to rise into management and\nhave control of school policies and so forth, like in a private company.\nThat's when happens in private enterprise. The people that excel end up in\nmanagement and they teach others and replicate their methods. But the public\nschool system structure offers little opportunity for advancement in that way.\nManagement is elected by popular vote, rather given as a reward for\nperformance. Policies are driven by political incentives rather than economic\nones. Teaching is really a dead end job, even if you are good at it.\n\nRespond\n\n### OldCurmudgeon\n\n2024-04-12 10:57:10\n\n52| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n>if they were working in organizations that allowed the better teachers to\nrise into management and have control of school policies and so forth\n\ntbh, I'd rather have the excellent teachers in the classroom, not the district\noffice. I'm also a little skeptical that the skills/qualities that make one a\ngood teacher translate into ed admin.\n\n(FWIW, I also think that many private businesses do this poorly. You should\njust pay the star engineer more, not \"promote\" them into a role with lots of\nemployee management and/or budget responsibilities)\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 11:15:48\n\n40| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nIt really depends on the individual. Is \"star engineer\" capable of (and\ninterested in) training other engineers in a way that improves company\nperformance? (Same with teachers). Of course some people just have an\nineffable thing and they can't communicate how they do it to others. Other\npeople are excellent at it and eager to communicate to management how to do\nthings better and more efficiently. The point is the option should be\navailable for teachers that have the ability to do so. Most people who have\nsome degree of talent at a thing are usually eager to show others how it's\ndone, in my experience.\n\nRespond\n\n### OldCurmudgeon\n\n2024-04-12 11:49:48\n\n24| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n>Is \"star engineer\" capable of (and interested in) training other engineers in\na way that improves company performance\n\nEven when true, I think I'd rather have my star technical people doing hard\ntechnical stuff. And have some other engineer who shows interest/aptidude for\ntraining new hires work in that role. Comparative advantage is my analogy\nhere.\n\nThe root of the issue, imho, is the rigid pay structure of most large orgs,\nwhere you have to get into a \"manager\" role to get a pay raise (and/or to not\nhave outsized compensation relative to others in your \"pay grade\") See also\nthe Peter Principal for further ineptness here.\n\nRespond\n\n### Roger Sweeny\n\n2024-04-12 11:04:28\n\n44| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThere is actually a fair amount of teacher collaboration, sharing what worked\nfor one teacher, trying to figure out why something isn't working for another.\nA lot of this is informal, though some schools schedule collaboration time for\nteachers.\n\nAround here, almost all \"management\", department heads, principals and\nassistant principals, even superintendents start out as teachers. Teaching is\ngenerally a dead end job because the pyramid is so flat. Compared to the\nnumber of teacher jobs, there are not many jobs \"above\" teacher.\n\nAnd those that are use a different skill set\n\nRespond\n\n### Engineer\n\n2024-04-12 09:30:09\n\n32| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThis basically captures the reality. The best thing we can do generally is\nscreen the really bad teachers out, and provide a good environment in the\nschools (civil, orderly, with an emphasis on excellence).\n\nThere are also some skill sets - math, science, IT - where you should expect\nto pay a premium to get competent people to teach.\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 09:27:57\n\n41| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nI don't think it is necessarily the case that \"good\" teachers would only want\nto work in \"good\" schools with \"good\" students. There are plenty of people out\nthere that like a challenge and would be excited to specialize in teaching\nstruggling students in poor school districts. I think the inhibitor is that if\nthey have to take a major pay cut to do so that makes it a less attractive\noption, even if they WANT to do it (because they have obligations to their\nfamily for instance). Also, I suspect the impact any one teacher can have is\nlimited because they cannot rise within the organization and reform how the\npublic schools are organized, they way they would in private enterprise. And\nthen they end up moving to charter schools and the like because they have\nslightly more influence over how the schools are run there.\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 09:31:57\n\n4| 2  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nHow many fast food CEOs started out working the fryer? Would things work\nbetter if more of them did?\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 09:50:41\n\n41| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nPoor analogy, IMO. Teachers are more like engineers than service people.\nThere's not a formula for teaching, like there is for assembling a hamburger.\nAnd there's a lot of possible innovation and room for improvement, that\nindividual teachers are capable of generating, which needs to flow vertically\nand horizontally to other teachers. The model where people get an MBA and then\ngo directly into management is already kind of dead in the tech sector anyway.\nMaybe it works for fast food restaurants, but IMO doesn't work very well in\nindustries where there's a need to innovate rapidly.\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 09:59:58\n\n5| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nEven in \"technology\", is it really dead for fundraisers and managers to be on\na somewhat separate track from engineers? Sam Altman seems like a career\nfundraiser, Tim Cook seems like he's always worked the business side, Pichai\nwent from a engineering degree to McKinsey to management at Google (at a\nglance).\n\nIf you can't systematize processes (no formula), then that's not very\noptimistic for productivity improvements.\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 11:26:00\n\n40| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nIf you can't systematize processes (no formula), then that's not very\noptimistic for productivity improvements.\n\nWell, yeah, but who is going to be good at doing the systematizing? The reason\nyou promote the best engineers into management is so that they can systemize\ntheir methods and transmit them across the organization. Because their\nknowledge of how they do the things is in their brain, not other people's\nbrains. And you can't just sit them down and have hours long conversations\nwith managers to teach them engineering and explain what they are doing.\nThat's not efficient.\n\nThe alternative model of course, is you have education departments doing\nstudies in universities and disseminating knowledge via higher education and\nsymposiums and stuff. But that has a whole other set of issues.\n\nMy point is, probably plenty of teachers would be willing to take on more\nchallenging jobs in poor school districts if there was a mechanism by which\nthat would actually lead to career advancement or higher pay. What's the point\nof doing that if it's just another dead end job, just with lower pay?\n\nRespond\n\n### Neurotic\n\n2024-04-12 11:26:08\n\n32| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nHM's claim that managing teachers, the parents, the public, the board, and the\nstate requires the same skill set as is found in good classroom teachers is\nabsurd.\n\nRespond\n\n### TMC\n\n2024-04-12 12:17:31\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"If you can't systematize processes....\" It would be nice to, but it may not\nbe possible. We can be open minded in who gets recruited to be teachers and\nhave a good process to winnow out the poor performers. This might work in its\nown right, or if we are lucky, will reveal some good recruitment avenues.\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 09:36:33\n\n4| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nI'm not decrying your comment or anything, but in reality aren't most business\npeople following a separate track from the people who are actually employed in\ntheir services? How much work would it take to make the head teacher to\neducation bureaucrat pathway as open as its comparable middle manager to\nsenior manager path in the private world?\n\nRespond\n\n### Hey rayward\n\n2024-04-12 08:44:27\n\n41| 2  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nYou know what you need? More quotes and parentheses.\n\nCome back when you are a big boy and can give us more quotes and parentheses.\n\nRespond\n\n### Slocum\n\n2024-04-12 08:34:28\n\n27| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nIn my state, good teachers already want to work in good schools in good\ndistricts with good (well-behaved, motivated) students -- quite apart from any\ndifference in salaries. And the benefits of seniority and connections tend to\nallow them to move to the schools they prefer. Also here, as in most states,\nsalaries do already vary between districts -- the union contracts are\nnegotiated at the district level, not the state level. What's lacking is pay\nfor performance *within* districts. And note that there would be nothing\npreventing districts from offering higher pay to teachers who were especially\neffective at teaching 'at risk' kids (in fact, this is something that my dark\nblue district might well do if it were possible).\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 09:32:51\n\n41| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nRight. Districts should really be paying MORE to teachers who are willing to\nteach at risk kids or kids that are struggling to catch up. Those should be\nchoice jobs that pay extra. Of course, part of the problem is that school\nfunding is tied to local property taxes so it's hard for schools in poor areas\nto afford to do that. And who is going to want to give money to a bunch of\nlocal school districts that are under performing , given the problems there\nmight be institutional dysfunction rather than teacher quality?\n\nRespond\n\n### Roger Sweeny\n\n2024-04-12 11:10:58\n\n44| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nIn my ideal world, districts would pay much more to teachers who could\nsignificantly bring up the performance of low achieving kids. Alas, very, very\nfew teachers like that seem to exist. And no one knows how to train people to\ndo that.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 11:30:25\n\n24| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThis has been tried, via \"No Child Left Behind\". The focus on low-achieving\nkids is having measurable deleterious impacts on the outcomes of middle- and\nhigh-achieving kids. It would not be entirely wrong to argue that this sort of\nmentality manufactures low-achieving students.\n\nRespond\n\n### Slocum\n\n2024-04-12 09:56:32\n\n24| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"part of the problem is that school funding is tied to local property taxes\"\n\nNot in Michigan since the 1990s. The state collects all property taxes for\nschool operations and redistributes the monies back to the districts on a per-\nstudent basis. Capital funding (school construction and maintenance, etc) is\nfunded directly by local property taxes, but operating funds come from the\nstate and cannot be topped up locally by voters approving higher tax rates.\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 09:45:55\n\n4| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\n\"To each the need\"?\n\nRespond\n\n### Hazel Meade\n\n2024-04-12 09:56:22\n\n41| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nSchool choice. Incentives drive people to reward performance. And hey, I could\nimagine a school district that is willing to innovate, even in a poor\nneighborhood, becoming an \"up and coming\" district because they are efficient,\nand high value compared to housing prices. That could be a thing.\n\nRespond\n\n### SB\n\n2024-04-12 08:33:24\n\n11| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nAmazingly bad comment here. Under the standard system you are glorifying, a\nbad school with bad students can do nothing to attract a good teacher because\nthey can\u2019t pay different from other schools. Under a pay for performance\nsystem, they can try to attract good teachers, or keep good ones they have, by\npaying them more.\n\nPeople! You can\u2019t rely on your intuition here! It will lead you astray. You\nneed to use your brain!\n\nRespond\n\n### Mcro\n\n2024-04-12 08:51:47\n\n18| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nThat doesn't work at all because nicer schools will have greater access to\nfunds than do poorer schools. Individually negotiated salaries will\nsupercharge the dynamic of the comment you're replying to.\n\nRespond\n\n### Slocum\n\n2024-04-12 12:24:29\n\n0| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\n\"That doesn't work at all because nicer schools will have greater access to\nfunds than do poorer schools. \"\n\nThat's not actually true. Some of the most dysfunctional urban public school\ndistricts have very high per-pupil funding. The Chicago Public Schools, for\nexample, spend $18K per student annually. This is more than the Illinois\naverage and MUCH more than the spending in other states in the region. But CPS\nproduces much worse outcomes with all the money it spends.\n\nRespond\n\n### MikeP\n\n2024-04-12 10:37:35\n\n21| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nWe still have a long way to go but COVID ... put a huge dent in the power of\nthe teacher\u2019s unions.\n\nWhat?\n\nThe teachers' unions that lined up gravestones because they were certain that\nchildren would kill them with covid?\n\nThe teachers' unions that got themselves vaccinated alongside health care\nworkers because they were essential workers and then still didn't allow in-\nperson schooling?\n\nThe teachers' unions that told the CDC what the rules needed to be to have in\nschools and then the CDC said that those were the rules needed to open up\nschools?\n\nThose teachers' unions?\n\nHas there been a backlash against these inconceivable abuses of demonstrated\nteachers' union power rained down upon the most vulnerable members of society\nand I missed it?\n\nRespond\n\n### Tomob\n\n2024-04-12 10:41:17\n\n20| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThe discussion of whether teachers unions are good or bad is a discussion\nabout the best way to fight over scraps. We should pay our teachers like we\npay airline pilots. We should put the real estate agents in charge of the\nschools, that's what they're selling when they market to families. Above all\npoliticians shut the goddamn hell up. High-end politicians scoring points on\nthe anxieties of parents, and pushing their various manufactured agendas is\none of the main reasons education is so screwed up.\n\nRespond\n\n### Jack\n\n2024-04-12 07:58:22\n\n19| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nDo we have an American model for hiring and promoting police officers? If not,\nwhy not?\n\nRespond\n\n### asdf\n\n2024-04-12 07:48:37\n\n19| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nI'd be interested to see how much of this is pay for performance and how much\nis pay by discipline. The big thing my magnet high school did was simply pay\nmore for STEM teachers then non-STEM. That seems to be the shortage that every\nschool faces, people with STEM skills have lots of high paying options outside\nthe teaching profession.\n\nRespond\n\n### Moral Panic\n\n2024-04-12 08:44:07\n\n43| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nOne thing I don't like is where teachers automatically get a pay raise for\nlife by getting an advanced degree. Doesn't matter whether the degree produced\na better teacher. Pure credentialism.\n\nDid my kids get a better result from Dr. So-and-so in middle school? No, other\nthan they learned at an early age that a person who always insisted on being\naddressed as \"Doctor\" was likely unimpressive.\n\nMy mother got a master's degree because she needed the money as a low-paid\nteacher in a rural district. She didn't think it made a lot of sense, yet she\nexplained that sometimes you gotta respond to incentives.\n\nRespond\n\n### Engineer\n\n2024-04-12 09:16:18\n\n32| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nIt\u2019s normally worse than that. The Masters degree they get is predominately in\neducation, which typically adds negative value. A masters in math or history\nis a rare outcome with the pay for certification programs.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 10:18:39\n\n24| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nHow do you propose we educate educators? Educating students is, after all, a\ndistinct skillset. We've both had classes in universities that were taught by\nprofessors who were experts in their field of study, and who had the teaching\nskills of an earthworm.\n\nRespond\n\n### OldCurmudgeon\n\n2024-04-12 11:08:47\n\n52| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nIn fairness, modern universities care about research output, not teaching.\nPresumably, K12 won't have that same motivation.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 11:57:02\n\n16| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nDepends on the university, but broadly true. But I didn't mean to imply that\nthis was exclusively a university issue; I was merely trying to find common\nground with Engineer, a shared experience that illustrates the flaw in his\nreasoning. I've dealt with similar teachers in the grade school and high\nschool level--people who no doubt are knowledgeable about the subject matter,\nbut who are incapable of teaching it.\n\nMy whole point is that teaching is a skillset, one that's unfortunately\nundervalued by the commentariat of this blog.\n\nRespond\n\n### TMC\n\n2024-04-12 10:30:24\n\n13| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nI'd prefer a teacher who has a degree in a subject, then a minor in teaching.\n\nRespond\n\n### Neurotic\n\n2024-04-12 11:38:30\n\n32| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nHow about a teacher who can teach kids the difference between 'then' and\n'than'?\n\nRespond\n\nContinue this thread \u2192\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 10:42:09\n\n24| 2  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAnd we're supposed to build our educational system to satisfy your individual\npreferences, in defiance of a wealth of data. We are supposed to satisfy your\nmere opinions at the cost of the entire field of pedagogy.\n\nThat's quite frankly stupid.\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 08:46:29\n\n4| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nDo you think her students got a better result from that than if she'd left the\neducation system for other employment/location? It's a shame it wasted her\nmoney and time buying/studying for the qualification though.\n\nRespond\n\n### Bob\n\n2024-04-12 09:13:05\n\n14| 0  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nDon't forget that what pay for performance also does is make everyone\nextremely aware of your definition of performance. When the job is complex\nenough, pay for performance just means the parts not in your performance\nmeasurement are abandoned. If you let someone decide subjectively, then the\nperformance function is 'find a boss who likes you'. If it is something the\nworker's effort doesn't control all that well within a school, like the\nquality of the students they get, then you'll get people fighting for the good\nschool location, which has most of the good kids, and the right grade which is\neasier to teach than the other.\n\nSo yes Alex, pay for performance is a powerful incentive, but many a manager\nthat has done this has gotten something a bit different than they thought they\nwere getting.\n\nRespond\n\n### Dinwar\n\n2024-04-12 10:02:34\n\n26| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThere's a joke in my industry: If you pay a driller by the foot you'll get one\nwell a thousand feet deep. If you pay by the well you'll get a hundred wells\nten feet deep. If you pay by the day you'll get one well ten feet deep.\n\nRespond\n\n### Max\n\n2024-04-12 08:00:14\n\n13| 1  \n---|---  \n  \nHide Replies\n\n#\n\nYou say this \"raised pay considerably\" but then the statistic you cite just\nnotes that the pay cap is way higher in districts that changed their\npractices. I doubt anyone, even the teachers unions, would have thought that\nthe pay cap for the highest paid teacher wouldn't go up in districts that\nreformed, so this doesn't seem responsive? And seems like more than ideal\nsalesmanship? (my prior fwiw is that average pay also went up, but would be\nnice to see that statistic)\n\nRespond\n\n### SB\n\n2024-04-12 08:44:34\n\n8| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nHe linked to the paper that has all the evidence. She didn\u2019t say \u201c I show that\nthe introduction of flexible pay raised salaries of high-quality teachers\u201d in\nthe abstract for no reason.\n\nRespond\n\n### MS\n\n2024-04-12 09:19:00\n\n8| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nAs I recall, Act 10 also mandated that average teacher pay not increase any\nfaster than inflation, therefore legally enforcing the Baumol effect and\ninsuring, over time, that teacher pay would become less and less competitive.\n\nRespond\n\n### M\n\n2024-04-12 07:39:23\n\n5| 0  \n---|---  \n  \n#\n\nThe statistical metric is higher, the costs and pay are higher. Is the metric\nworth the cost increase? Perhaps you need a separate indicator for that...\n\nRespond\n\nRespond\n\n### Marginal Revolution University\n\nSee Courses\n\n### Learn more about Mercatus Center Fellowships\n\nLearn More\n\n### Subscribe via Email\n\n  * RSS Feed\n\n## Contact Us\n\nAlex Tabarrok Email Alex Follow @atabarrok\n\nTyler Cowen E